<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="aa-section-turntable-subsection-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Expanding the total derivative of <m>\hat{i}</m></title>

  <p>
    The orientations of the unit direction vectors of the local Cartesian coordinate system can change
    depending on where their anchoring point is placed on the turntable or above or below it.
    Furthermore, they and their point rotate along with the turntable.
    Consequently, <m>\hat{i} = \hat{i}(\lambda, R, z)</m>,
    <m>\hat{j} = \hat{j}(\lambda, R, z)</m>,
    and <m>\hat{k} = \hat{k}(\lambda, R, z)</m>,
    and <m>\lambda = \lambda(t)</m>,
    <m>R = R(t)</m>,
    and <m>z = z(t)</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    We will start by using the chain rule to expand <m>\dfrac{D \hat{i}}{Dt}</m>.
    This will give us insight into how <m>\hat{i}</m> changes orientation as the turntable rotates.
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-i-full-turntable" number="yes"> 
      \frac{D \hat{i}}{Dt}
      =
      \frac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial \lambda}
      \frac{D \lambda}{Dt}
      +
      \frac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial R}
      \frac{DR}{Dt}
      +
      \frac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial z}
      \frac{Dz}{Dt}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    The second term on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-i-full-turntable" text="type-global" />
    is <m>\vec{0}</m> since <m>\hat{i}</m> does not change orientation if placed at a different radius
    while holding <m>\lambda</m> and <m>z</m> constant,
    and therefore <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial R} = \vec{0}</m>.
    Furthermore, the point does not move from the edge of the turntable,
    and so <m>\dfrac{DR}{Dt} = 0</m>.
    Likewise, the third term on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-i-full-turntable" text="type-global" />
    is <m>\vec{0}</m> since <m>\hat{i}</m> does not change orientation if placed at a different height above or below the turntable
    while holding <m>\lambda</m> and <m>R</m> constant,
    and therefore <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial z} = \vec{0}</m>.
    Furthermore, the point does not move above or below the edge of the turntable,
    and so <m>\dfrac{Dz}{Dt} = 0</m>.
    Therefore, <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-i-full-turntable" text="type-global" /> reduces to
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-i-reduced-turntable" number="yes"> 
      \frac{D \hat{i}}{Dt}
      =
      \frac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial \lambda}
      \frac{D \lambda}{Dt}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    To evaluate <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{i}}{\partial \lambda}</m>,
    we consider the change in <m>\hat{i}</m>'s orientation
    when its anchoring point is fixed to the edge of the turntable
    and sweeps through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m> over time <m>\delta t</m>,
    as shown in <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-start" text="type-global" /> below.
    <m>\hat{i}_1</m> is the initial position of <m>\hat{i}</m>,
    and <m>\hat{i}_2</m> is the final position of <m>\hat{i}</m> after time <m>\delta t</m> has passed
    and it has swept through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-i-start">
    <caption>
      Unit direction vectors <m>\hat{i}_1</m> and <m>\hat{i}_2</m> at two nearby points at radius <m>R</m> to the turntable of
      <xref ref="aa-turntable-setup" text="type-global" />
      and separated by angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/aa-turntable-i-start.png" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
        Two unit direction vectors at two nearby points
        on the edge of a circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above.
        The vectors point tangent to the edge of the disk.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Fixing the tails of <m>\hat{i}_1</m> and <m>\hat{i}_2</m> together in
    <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-zoom" text="type-global" /> below
    reveals that <m>\delta \lambda</m> is the angle swept out between them
    and <m>\vec{\delta i}</m> is the vector difference between them.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-i-zoom">
    <caption>
      Reproduction of <m>\hat{i}_1</m> and <m>\hat{i}_2</m> from <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-start" text="type-global" />.
      When the tails of the vectors are fixed together,
      they are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta i}</m>.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/aa-turntable-i-zoom.png" width="40%">
      <shortdescription>
        Two unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
        and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Reproducing <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-start" text="type-global" />
    with the tail of <m>\hat{i}_1</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{i}_2</m> and <m>\vec{\delta i}</m> additionally included
    in <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-end" text="type-global" /> below makes these relationships even clearer.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="aa-turntable-i-end">
    <caption>
      Reproduction of <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-start" text="type-global" />
      with the tail of <m>\hat{i}_1</m> fixed to the tail of <m>\hat{i}_2</m>.
      As shown in <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-zoom" text="type-global" />,
      <m>\hat{i}_1</m> and <m>\hat{i}_2</m> are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m>
      and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta i}</m>.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/aa-turntable-i-end.png" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
        Two unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
        on the edge of a circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    We can use the arc length formula to approximate <m>|\vec{\delta i}|</m>,
    and we can take advantage of the fact that,
    since <m>\hat{i}</m> is a unit direction vector,
    <m>|\hat{i}| = 1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <md number="yes">
      |\vec{\delta i}|
      = |\hat{i_1}| \, \delta \lambda
      = |\hat{i_2}| \, \delta \lambda
      = |\hat{i}| \, \delta \lambda
      = \delta \lambda
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Therefore,
  </p>

  <p>
    <md number="yes">
      \frac{|\vec{\delta i}|}{\delta t}
      =
      \frac{|\vec{\delta i}|}{\delta \lambda}
      \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t}
      =
      \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta \lambda}
      \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t}
      =
      \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    From <xref ref="aa-turntable-i-end" text="type-global" />,
    we can see that as <m>\delta t \to 0</m>,
    <m>\delta \lambda \to 0</m> and <m>\vec{\delta i}</m> points directly inward toward the center of the turntable,
    which coincides with the <m>\hat{j}</m> direction.
    So
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-i-final-turntable" number="yes"> 
      \lim_{\delta t \to 0}
      \frac{\vec{\delta i}}{\delta t}
      =
      \frac{D \hat{i}}{D t}
      =
      \lim_{\delta t \to 0}
      \frac{\delta \lambda}{\delta t} \, \hat{j}
      =
      \frac{D\lambda}{Dt} \, \hat{j}
      =
      \Omega \, \hat{j}
    </md>
  </p>

</subsection>